%N A394643 Total number of cells under all symmetric Dyck paths of semilength n in the first quadrant of the square grid.
%C A394643 The total number of cells equals the total area under all symmetric Dyck paths.
%C A394643 Equivalently, total number of cells above all symmetric Dyck paths of semilength n in the fourth quadrant of the square grid.
%H A394643 Alois P. Heinz, <a href="/A394643/b394643.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..3305</a>
%F A394643 a(n) = (A057571(n) + A001405(n)*n^2)/2. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Mar 27 2026
%e A394643 For n = 3 there are three symmetric Dyck paths of semilength 3 in the first quadrant of the square grid as shown below:
%e A394643     _          _ _        _ _ _
%e A394643      |_           |_           |
%e A394643        |_           |          |
%e A394643          |          |          |
%e A394643 .
%e A394643 The total number of cells under the symmetric Dyck paths is 6 + 8 + 9 = 23 as shown below:
%e A394643     _          _ _        _ _ _
%e A394643    |_|_       |_|_|_     |_|_|_|
%e A394643    |_|_|_     |_|_|_|    |_|_|_|
%e A394643    |_|_|_|    |_|_|_|    |_|_|_|
%e A394643       6          8          9
%e A394643 .
%e A394643 So a(3) = 23.
%p A394643 b:= proc(x, y) option remember; `if`(y<0 or y>x, 0, `if`(x=0, [1, 0],
%p A394643       add((p-> p+[0, p[1]*(2*y+i)])(b(x-1, y+i)), i=[-1, 1])))
%p A394643     end:
%p A394643 a:= n-> (add(b(n, n-2*i), i=0..n/2)[2]+binomial(n, floor(n/2))*n^2)/2:
%p A394643 seq(a(n), n=0..30);  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Apr 01 2026
